    ergonomics

    noun, plural in form but singular or plural in construction
    Save Word

    To save this word, you'll need to log in.

    Log In 
    er·​go·​nom·​ics | \ ˌər-gə-ˈnä-miks \

    Definition of ergonomics

    1 : an applied science concerned with designing and arranging things people use so that the people and things interact most efficiently and safely

    — called also biotechnology, human engineering, human factors

    2 : the design characteristics of an object resulting especially from the application of the science of ergonomics
    Other Words from ergonomics Example Sentences Learn More About ergonomics

    Other Words from ergonomics

    ergonomic \ ˌər-​gə-​ˈnä-​mik \ adjective
    ergonomically \ ˌər-​gə-​ˈnä-​mi-​k(ə-​)lē \ adverb
    ergonomist \ (ˌ)ər-​ˈgä-​nə-​mist \ noun

    Examples of ergonomics in a Sentence

    Recent Examples on the Web Despite its pre-build plastics, the Emira's interior also impressed, with soft facings on the doors and dashboard and good ergonomics. — Mike Duff, Car and Driver, 8 Mar. 2022 The road to building a good all-terrain wheelchair is littered with broken axles, gravel road rash, and uncomfortable ergonomics; just ask Geoff Babb. — Emily Pennington, Outside Online, 25 July 2020 Overall, the Tundra's cabin is highlighted by excellent ergonomics and a straightforward design, including our truck's simple analog gauges flanking an intuitive 4.2-inch display; a vibrant 12.3-inch digital cluster is standard on higher trims. — Mike Sutton, Car and Driver, 30 Mar. 2022

    First Known Use of ergonomics

    1949, in the meaning defined at sense 1

    History and Etymology for ergonomics

    erg- + -nomics (as in economics)
